In this assignment we will focus on longer term forecast as it is appropriate for aggregate planning and/or facilities planning.

We are interested in obtaining a 5 year forecast (60 months to be precise) of the size of the grocery store market in the US, and we want that forecast in monthly (not weekly) intervals. Such a forecast is useful if you are preparing an infrastructure plan for a grocery store chain for example: this type of forecast is useful to make decisions about number of new stores to open, number of distribution centers and their capacity, personnel and other infrastructure decisions.

The data set MRTSSM4451USN.csv includes monthly retail sales of grocery stores in the US from January 1992 through December 2017 expressed in millions of US dollars.
Source: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MRTSSM4451USN

The first thing we need to do is load the data file and convert it into an appropriate time-series object. This is accomplished with the following code:

library(fpp2)
library(dplyr)
#
# Read csv file and make it a time series
GS <- read.csv("MRTSSM4451USN.csv") %>%
  select(-DATE) %>%
  ts(start= c(1992,1), frequency=12)

In this assignment we will learn to use the ets() function to fit and analyze exponential smoothing models. Before proceeding to fit a model we examine and divide the data into two sets; a training set tr that we will use to fit the models and a testing (or hold-out) data set te to assess the out-of-sample performance of the models. This is accomplished with the following code:

## Training set
tr <- window(GS, end=c(2011,12))
## Testing Set
te <- window(GS, start=c(2012,1))

autoplot(GS) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=2012.0, color="gray") +
  ggtitle("Monthly Sales of US Grocery Stores")

The Above analysis was carried out by using a smoothing model with additive errors. Upon looking at the plot of the time series, it appears that it has a positive trend and monthly seasonality. However, The trend component was not incorporated in our model as it is damped in our model. This is because of forcing additive error model on the data. This resulted in a relatively detrend forecast for next 72 months, where as the actuals trend increased progressively

It is due to the same above mentioned reason that, by looking at individual in-sample metrics, the errors values are coming up to be high, which are further getting increased when calculating on out of sample (show in out-of-sample metrics)

By looking at teh out of sample MASE, since it is greater than 1, it can be said that the model is performing worse than the Naive model on test dataset. Thus we can choose Niave model over this model

We can see there is a huge difference between the evaluation metrics. It is because the optimized model is incorporating the trend of the time series while forecasting.

The confidence interval cones of both models expands as the forecasted year value increases. If going by the previous model in operations, the amount of storage inventory will increase linearly as the months will pass by because the confidence cone widens as forecasted months increase. This increase in uncertainity will add to increase in cost and add also the risk because the confidence cone has an equivalent negitive demand as well If going by this model (fc.hw2) the demand is varying proportional with the confidence interval, so the storage inventory will also vary accordingly, sometimes increasing and decreasing. This can lead to flexible storage based on demand with varying cost

However, in both cases, as the number of months increases, the range of values increases, thus adding to uncertainity. Due to this, it is better to forecast again at specific periods so that the confidence range is within desirable limits

### Fitting the ets function with additive errors (ANN)
lmbda_arry <- data.frame()

for(i in 1992:2006){
  #print(i)
  dftemp <- df[which(df$year2>=i),]
  dftemp2 <- dftemp$Y
  trtemp <- ts(dftemp2,start= c(i,1), frequency=12)
  L <- BoxCox.lambda(trtemp)
  z <- BoxCox(trtemp,L)
  
  fl.0 <- ets(trtemp, model = "ZZZ", restrict  = FALSE)
  flc.O <- forecast(fl.0, h = 72)
  acctr1 <- (accuracy(flc.O,te))
  
  flB.O <- ets(trtemp, model = "ZZZ", restrict  = FALSE, lambda = L)
  flcb.O <- forecast(flB.O, h = 72)
  acctr2 <- (accuracy(flcb.O,te))
  
  flB.OD <- ets(trtemp, model = "ZZZ", restrict  = FALSE, lambda = L, damped = TRUE)
  flcB.OD <- forecast(flB.OD, h = 72)
  acctr4 <- accuracy(flcB.OD,te)
  
  lmbda_arry <- rbind(lmbda_arry,c(L,i,acctr1[3],acctr2[3],acctr4[3]))

We cannot choose the AIC , BIC and AICc values as they are scaled values of the inner model. Also, since the data window will be changing the AIC, BIC values will keep on improving as they are inversely proportional to the amount of the data. Thus, selecting the model based on these criterias will not give us the desired resutls

The AICc is not comparable with the f.0. This is the box-cox transformation forecast, which first standardizes the data and then computes the AICc. Thus the value opbtained is on the scaled data which is different from the one calculated on the raw data by f.O. Thus, they both are not computed with the same data and cannot be compared

The MASE is computed on the model output and because of this, the MASE is comparable between f.o and f, as they both are computed on the same data and can be compared to the naive model

Due to the same reasons, the out of sample RMSE can also be compared. The fc forecast is not truly the out of sample forecast because the optimum value of lambda is chosen by using in-sample RMSE metric on different data windows.
